---
import Layout from '@/layouts/Layout.astro';
import PageMeta from '@/components/PageMeta.astro';
---
<Layout
  title="Mapping — Coverage & gaps"
  description="What the RML mapping covers, what it honestly doesn't, and why 469 — not the raw 8,458-leaf schema dictionary — is the right denominator."
>
<PageMeta category="Coverage register" variant="warn" updated="Updated 2026-07-05" damaKa={["Metadata Management", "Data Integration & Interoperability"]} />

  <h1>Coverage &amp; gaps</h1>
  <p class="lead">
    The mapping's own discipline is "bind only what exists" — a schema location with no sound
    ontology predicate is left in a gap register, never force-bound to a plausible-looking
    term. This page is that register, plus the vocabulary needed to read it correctly.
  </p>

  <nav class="callout callout--note" aria-label="On this page">
    <div class="callout__label">On this page</div>
    <ul style="margin: 0;">
      <li><a href="#vocab">Layer 1, layer 2, and GAP</a></li>
      <li><a href="#current">The current figure</a></li>
      <li><a href="#scope">Why 469, not 8,458</a></li>
      <li><a href="#honest">Honest non-mapping, worked</a></li>
    </ul>
  </nav>

  <h2 id="vocab">Layer 1, layer 2, and GAP</h2>
  <p>The mapping's build contract (<code>CONTRACT.md</code>) defines three tiers:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Layer 1 — provenance-anchored.</strong> Every schema leaf that some
      <code>opda:</code> predicate's own <code>dct:source</code> citation names, inverted back
      into a mapping rule. Authoritative and unambiguous — the mapping's "sound AND complete"
      claim applies to layer 1 only.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Layer 2 — shared/collapsed leaves.</strong> Semantically the same shared property
      (e.g. a supplier name, an address part) but not itself a <code>dct:source</code> target.
      Mapped best-effort, with an explicit coverage report — never silently claimed complete.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>GAP.</strong> A schema location, or an ontology resource, with no sound
      counterpart on the other side. Expected and logged, not a completeness failure — the
      alternative (force-binding a plausible-but-wrong predicate) is the one thing this
      mapping is designed never to do.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <div class="callout callout--note">
    <div class="callout__label">"Gap register" means two different things on this site</div>
    <p>
      This mapping's own gap register (<code>gap-register.json</code> /
      <code>build/final-gap.json</code>) tracks schema↔ontology mapping gaps. The GAP register
      on <a href="/ontology/known-issues#thin">Ontology → Known issues</a> tracks a completely
      different thing — which overlay <em>profiles</em> bind which Category-G leaves. Same
      name, two unrelated pipelines; don't conflate a figure from one with the other.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="current">The current figure</h2>
  <p>
    As of 2026-07-05, <strong>466 of 469 domain-module ontology resources are mapped or
    removed for cause — 99.4%</strong> (<code>source/03-standards/rml/build/final-gap.json</code>,
    regenerate with <code>python3 build/final_scope2.py</code> — see
    <a href="/mapping/validate">Running &amp; validating</a>). The 3 remaining are:
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Term</th><th>Kind</th><th>Domain → Range</th><th>Why it stays unmapped</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>opda:founds</code></td><td>ObjectProperty</td><td>Relator → Role</td><td rowspan="3">UFO Role/Relator connectives asserting an <em>alternate encoding</em> of a fact the mapping already captures via co-typing (e.g. <code>?s a opda:Seller</code> directly) + <code>opda:roleNotation</code>. There is structurally no distinct Role node for these edges to target under this ontology's chosen encoding — not an oversight, a standing exclusion rule for upper-ontology/structural-pattern terms.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>opda:playedBy</code></td><td>ObjectProperty</td><td>Role → Organisation</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>opda:plays</code></td><td>ObjectProperty</td><td>Organisation → Role</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p class="muted tiny">
    This is the outcome of a long gap-closing effort, not a static number: earlier points in
    the same effort recorded 465/472 (98.5%) and 459/472 (97.2%). Three resources
    (<code>UPRNSuccessionEvent</code>, <code>AssuranceLevel</code>, <code>inspireFeatureId</code>)
    were removed outright late in that effort, confirmed to have zero basis anywhere in the
    schema corpus — not merely unpopulated in the tracked fixtures — which is why the
    denominator moved from 472 to 469. Full session-by-session detail:
    <a href="/modelling/adr/adr-0057">ADR-0057</a>'s Amendments.
  </p>

  <h2 id="scope">Why 469, not 8,458</h2>
  <p>
    The canonical PDTF data dictionary has 8,458 leaf records. It is tempting to divide the
    mapping's coverage by that number instead — this project tried exactly that, twice, in the
    same session that closed the last few gaps, and both attempts were wrong for the same
    reason: <strong>the raw dictionary was never the ontology's target coverage scope.</strong>
    It is the mechanical supply an upstream curation pass (Category A–G, ODR-0022) consumes,
    not a checklist the ontology must equal. That curation's completed output — 469
    domain-module resources — is the correct, complete denominator; 8,458 (or the ~7,810 /
    ~2,164 "still to map" figures briefly proposed before the error was caught) measures the
    wrong thing entirely.
  </p>

  <h2 id="honest">Honest non-mapping, worked</h2>
  <p>Two real leaves illustrate the discipline of leaving a gap rather than force-binding it:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong><code>propertyPack.priceInformation.price</code></strong> (the headline asking
      price) has no sound predicate to bind to. <code>opda:soldPrice</code> /
      <code>opda:listPrice</code> / <code>opda:estimatedPrice</code> are all
      <code>opda:Valuation</code>-domain <em>comparable</em> prices, and <code>opda:price</code>
      is a separate, Category-D fixtures amount — none mean "this property's current asking
      price." It stays a gap; closing it needs a genuine ontology addition
      (e.g. a new <code>opda:askingPrice</code>), not a mapping change.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong><code>propertyPack.connectivity.broadband.supplier</code></strong> is not the
      <code>dct:source</code> of any predicate either, but it <em>is</em> semantically the
      shared <code>opda:supplier</code> property used elsewhere — so it's mapped as layer 2,
      best-effort, rather than left in the gap register.
    </li>
  </ul>
</Layout>
